<Base
  title="How It Started"
  description="The origin of Project Cognify — how three students turned a shared frustration with focus into a seven-month research project."
>
  <h1>How It Started</h1>
  <p class="label">How Project Cognify began</p>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2>It Started With One Question</h2>
    <p>
      One night, Jonathan and Jeremy stayed up until 2:00 AM playing a newly
      released Roblox update. Neither of them wanted to go to sleep because they
      knew they'd wake up to spoilers all over social media.
    </p>
    <p>The next day, one question kept coming up.</p>
    <p>
      Why is it so easy to spend hours focused on a game, yet so difficult to
      stay focused on schoolwork?
    </p>
    <p>
      At first, it felt like a random observation. But the more Jonathan thought
      about it, the more he realized it wasn't just his experience. Nearly every
      student he knew struggled with the same thing.
    </p>
    <p>
      Instead of assuming he already knew the answer, he decided to investigate
      it.
    </p>

    <h2>Turning an Idea into a Team</h2>
    <p>
      Jonathan had worked with Jeremy and Ryan during a game jam the year
      before. They approached problems differently, but they worked well
      together and weren't afraid to challenge each other's ideas.
    </p>
    <p>
      When Jonathan shared the question that had been stuck in his head, neither
      of them asked what app they were going to build.
    </p>
    <p>They asked a different question.</p>
    <p>"What do we actually know?"</p>
    <p>The honest answer was... not much.</p>
    <p>
      That realization changed the direction of the project. Instead of jumping
      straight into building, the team decided to start with research.
    </p>
    <p>That was the start of Project Cognify.</p>

    <h2>Following the Evidence</h2>
    <p>
      Like many students, we've experienced how difficult it can be to stay
      focused when everything around us is competing for our attention.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our first idea centered around FOMO. We wondered if the same psychology
      that keeps people engaged in games could somehow be used to help students
      stay focused while studying.
    </p>
    <p>But we didn't want to build something based on assumptions.</p>
    <p>
      So we started reading academic research, surveying students, conducting
      interviews, and documenting everything we learned.
    </p>
    <p>The research didn't simply support our original idea.</p>
    <p>It changed it.</p>
    <p>
      Today, our work is focused on understanding how motivation, social
      presence, and accountability influence attention, and using that evidence
      to guide what we build next.
    </p>

    <h2>Building as We Learn</h2>
    <p>
      One thing we've learned throughout this project is that research and
      building don't have to happen separately.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every paper we read, every interview we conduct, and every survey response
      helps shape the next version of our ideas.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our first prototype, <a href="/cohort">Cohort</a>, is one example of that
      process. It isn't meant to prove we're right. It's designed to test a
      question and help us learn something new.
    </p>
    <p>
      If the evidence changes our thinking again, we'll change the product too.
    </p>

    <h2>Why We're Sharing the Journey</h2>
    <p>Most student projects only show the finished result.</p>
    <p>We wanted to share everything that happens before that.</p>
    <p>
      This website is where we document our research, our questions, our
      prototypes, the mistakes we make, and the lessons we learn along the way.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whether Project Cognify succeeds or fails, we hope someone else can learn
      as much from the journey as from the outcome.
    </p>

    <h2>A Note from the Team</h2>
    <p>
      We're three high school students who became curious about a question we
      couldn't stop thinking about.
    </p>
    <p>
      We don't have all the answers, and we expect our ideas to keep changing as
      we learn more.
    </p>
    <p>That's the whole point.</p>
    <p>Thanks for following along.</p>
  </div>
</Base>

